{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488906","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488906"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:01:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:01:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"571"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"571","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/571"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.15,0.03,0.61,0.16]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"571"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111905"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"571","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/571"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"571"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93968"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"181"},{"type":"tags","id":"214"},{"type":"tags","id":"582"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"1149"},{"type":"tags","id":"9270"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4981"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6279"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45661"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111905","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111905"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with abdominal discomfort and fever. He describes a four-week history of increasing abdominal distension, now associated with breathlessness and dizziness when lying flat. His medical history includes hypertension, atrial fibrillation, and type 2 diabetes mellitus. His medications include metformin, warfarin, and perindopril.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell with scleral icterus. His pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 110/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 38.2\u00b0C. His abdomen is distended but not tense, with prominent superficial veins and shifting dullness. There is bilateral non-tender scrotal swelling that transilluminates.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood tests reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlanine transferase 120 U/L (5-40)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAspartate transferase 140 U/L (5-40)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBilirubin 30 \u00b5mol/L (2-24)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlbumin 28 g/L (34-48)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInternational Normalised Ratio 2.5 (0.9-1.2)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of the bilateral scrotal swelling?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Epididymitis","Idiopathic scrotal oedema","Inguinal hernias","Hydrocele","Varicocele"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features of decompensated cirrhosis including ascites, jaundice, possible coagulopathy, and hypoalbuminaemia. The bilateral scrotal swelling that transilluminates is consistent with hydroceles secondary to portal hypertension and hypoalbuminaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHydrocele\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely diagnosis. In the context of portal hypertension and low albumin, fluid can accumulate in dependent areas including the scrotum. The key examination finding of transillumination is pathognomonic for hydrocele, which represents fluid collection within the tunica vaginalis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEpididymitis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with acute onset of unilateral scrotal pain and swelling, often with associated fever and urinary symptoms. The non-tender nature of this patient\u0027s scrotal swelling makes epididymitis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIdiopathic scrotal oedema\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily a condition of young children, presenting with acute onset of erythematous scrotal wall swelling. It would be extremely unusual in an adult with clear underlying cause for the swelling.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInguinal hernias\u003C/strong\u003E do not typically transilluminate and would be reducible unless strangulated. They usually present with a visible bulge in the groin that extends into the scrotum and changes with position or Valsalva maneuver.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVaricocele\u003C/strong\u003E presents as a \u0027bag of worms\u0027 on palpation due to dilated veins of the pampiniform plexus. While portal hypertension can cause varicoceles, they do not transilluminate and are typically unilateral (left-sided).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hydroceles are non-tender scrotal swellings that transilluminate on examination","Portal hypertension from cirrhosis can cause bilateral hydroceles due to increased venous pressure and hypoalbuminaemia","The combination of jaundice, coagulopathy, and hypoalbuminaemia suggests decompensated cirrhosis"],"references":["Crawford P, Crop JA. Evaluation of scrotal masses. Am Fam Physician. 2014 May 1; 89(9):723-7","Acute scrotal pain or swelling [Internet]. Melbourne VIC: Royal Children\u0027s Hospital; 2020 July [cited 2022 April 14]. Available from: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/Acute_scrotal_pain_or_swelling/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93968"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"571"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93968","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93968"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-21T09:35:53+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-21T09:36:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"571"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111905"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduatin